John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scottish independent schools maintain a curriculum of academic excellence and this has continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding test scores, bolstered by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other collective efforts.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best level of service to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further higher education, their chosen career and their place in the world as global citizens.
As an education sector capable of developing and adopting a personalized school curriculum, we note that modern languages continue to be a popular and in-demand subject within schools.
Nelson Mandela said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message will come to his brain.
If you speak to him in his mother tongue, the message will reach his heart.”
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone if we want to build trusting relationships with people from other countries.
From the results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
68% of students who studied foreign languages received the highest marks.
The data, collected from 74 SCIS member schools, showed that 72% of students received the highest grade with praise in Chinese, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish received the highest grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as core skills for children and young people, who will undoubtedly need them in the future.
Currently, languages, as a choice of subject, are considered at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, technique and mathematics) in the curricula of independent institutes and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that the reasons employees indicated for the difficulty in filling jobs are attributable in 17% of cases to a lack of language skills.
This is why language skills are becoming increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more job opportunities requiring language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if you have learned a second language, you will have an effective advantage in the future with a lifetime competence like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will automatically lead a multilingual person to the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language at a level sufficient to maintain a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%.
That’s why investing in language teaching is so important for today’s children.
Knowledge of more languages, particularly those in developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages taught.
Several schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK looking at 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be several languages to choose from in independent schools, with teaching staff specializing in this area.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills needed for success, whatever their future.
It is not possible to deny at this time, in a global trading system, that languages continue to be fundamental for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in teaching.
Indeed, modern languages should be considered "international communication skills."
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
We have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
