"However, we do not see any compliant response from the United States," he said.
“Without trust in the U.S. there will be no security in our national security and in such circumstances we absolutely refuse to unilaterally disarm ourselves first.”
Although Ri has reused known complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization with which North Korea would be rewarded on the basis of gradual actions, his statement was important because he did not entirely reject unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang has already done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first-ever meeting between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work toward “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula,” while Trump promised North Korean security guarantees.
North Korea sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States said Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also opposed calls to loosen rigid international sanctions on North Korea.
“The U.S. insists on the need to “have denuclearization first” and to increase the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve their purpose in a coercive manner and even opposes the “declaration of the end of the war,” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an illusion of those who don’t know anything about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions is increasing our distrust.”
Ri did not refer to plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the US leader had announced at the UN earlier this week.
The minister stressed the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past five months and added: "If the counterpart to this issue of denuclearization were South Korea and not the United States, denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be dead at this point."
But even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was markedly different from last year’s speech at the UN General Assembly, when he said it was inevitable to target U.S. territory with North Korea’s missiles after “evil president” Trump had called Kim a “missile man” engaged in a suicide mission.
Trump, who last year threatened to “completely destroy” North Korea, praised Kim for his courage in embarking on the disarmament path, but said much more needs to be done and that sanctions will remain in place until North Korea is denuclearized.
