Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has pushed all of its students to sleep longer in an attempt to counteract the growing masculine culture of studying for whole nights powered by caffeine.
One university scholar found that students at the world’s number one university often have no idea of the basic concepts of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, developed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
She had the idea to start the course after a lecture she had given on the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
“In the end, a girl came to me and said, ‘Why am I only being told this now, when I’m in my senior year?’
She said no one had ever told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me a lot," she told The Telegraph.
The course, given for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep-related habits can help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general manager of the university’s health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive activities.
In one section there is the image of a dormitory room, where students can select coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of an evening routine.
In another section, participants are explained how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risks of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that it will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe they have a right to know, just as they have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes,” added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride linked to the “blank night studying” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students lead to lack of sleep being an ever-growing problem.
Getting enough sleep and with good quality sleep should be students’ “secret weapon” to fight stress, fatigue, anxiety, he explained and even should serve to avoid getting fat since lack of sleep brings the brain into starvation mode, making people constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student enrolled in the faculty of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course after taking one of his lectures last year during his first year at Harvard.
He explained that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a course aimed at the entire campus.
