Red tide update: concentration decreases in Pinellas, Manatee and Sarasota
The latest report from the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows an overall decrease in red tide concentration in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, patchy flowering conditions, which suggest a decrease in concentration, are evident in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties.
The red tide flowering stretches for about 130 miles of coastline from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
The patches are located about 10 miles off Hillsborough County but in fewer areas than last week.
The red tide has also been observed in Pasco County.
Last week an average concentration in Pinellas County or off its coasts, a concentration from low to high off Hillsborough County, from a background concentration to a low concentration in Manatee County, from a background concentration to a high concentration in Sarasota County or off its coasts, from a background concentration to an average concentration in Charlotte County, from a background concentration to a background concentration in Charlotte County, was reported.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in the counties of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier.
No cases were reported in northwest Florida last week.
